          "payload": {},
          "sequence": 44,
          "subtype": "message",
          "text": "Let me create a summary of my fault localization findings:\n\n## Summary of Fault Localization\n\nI've analyzed the ACPI video backlight control failure on the Acer TravelMate 5735Z and identified the root cause:\n\n### **Buggy File**: `drivers/platform/x86/acer-wmi.c`\n\n### **Buggy Data Structure**: `video_vendor_dmi_table` (lines 584-637)\n\n### **Root Cause Analysis**:\n\n1. **Problem**: The Acer TravelMate 5735Z is **missing** from the `video_vendor_dmi_table` in acer-wmi.c\n   \n2. **Why this breaks brightness control**:\n   - The `video_vendor_dmi_table` contains DMI entries for Acer machines that should use native/ACPI video backlight instead of acer-wmi's interface\n   - When a device is not in this table, acer-wmi doesn't call `video_set_backlight_video_vendor` to disable brightness capability\n   - The device falls back to `quirk_unknown` which has `brightness = 0` (default)\n   - Since `brightness >= 0` (line 926), the `ACER_CAP_BRIGHTNESS` capability is enabled (line 927)\n   - acer-wmi registers a brightness backlight device\n   - This interferes with the native intel_backlight driver\n\n3. **Evidence**:\n   - User reports `acpi_backlight=native` parameter **works perfectly** with 15-16 brightness levels\n   - Similar Acer TravelMate models (4750, 5760, etc.) are already in the `video_vendor_dmi_table`\n   - The pattern clearly shows these models need the native backlight handler\n\n4. **The Fix**:\n   - Add an entry for TravelMate 5735Z to `video_vendor_dmi_table` with callback `video_set_backlight_video_vendor`\n   - This will disable `ACER_CAP_BRIGHTNESS` capability for this model\n   - acer-wmi won't interfere with native backlight\n   - System will properly use intel_backlight/ACPI video for brightness control\n\n**Confidence: 0.95** (Very high confidence in this localization)\n\nThe result has been written to `/workspace/fault_localization_result.json`.",
